{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs20 My name is Joshua Jacob Voth. But thanks to my time on Homeworld and the Homeworlders' weird customs i am now know to most as "Voth". I am an aide to Balthazar, one of the most influential men in the entire Portal Network. This is the story of how he came to be so: \par
\par
It wasnt the actual unpleasantness of vomiting that bothered him - the food had weighed so uncomfortably on his stomach it was actually a relief to be rid of it. what bothered Balthazar was the fact that the old Artisan had been right, he had just wasted half a day's water ration on a meal of salads, fruits and drinks. Now it was just a fast disappearing dark patch on a rock in the baking heat of the noonday sun, the mess of solids having already attracted cleaner beetles from miles around. Balthazar should have listened to the old man's unsolicited but apparently accurate advice about not eating. It was as if there were side effects of the jump that reached backward in time. This Balthazar knew was impossible, yet so much popular myth surrounded the nature of portal travel that it conveniently warped the basic truth that the prospect of a portal jump was inherently risky enough to give anyone a deep nervous knot in the pit of their stomach. Yet in Balthazar's case it was not pure fear, he had had the confidence to ignore the old man and brazenly wolf down a meal since he was nearly as both aflicted with the arrogance of youth and truly as excited as he was nervous, unfortunately it seemed his excitement was just as unsettling as his fear.\par
\tab As the blinkered tunnel vison from hurling his stomach contents onto the flagstones withdrew, Balthazar realised the old Artisan working on the fountain in the courtyard was chuckling at Balthazar's upset with great delight, something only one who worked with water so regularly could comfortably do when from a thouroughly dessicated world such as Homeworld. Even in this particular antechamber of the portal hive buildings open water in the form of a fountain and cistern, a luxury usually reserved for those of great wealth and status, was an unexpected feature. Like the old man, Balthazar was not so fascinated as would be expected of one native to this world, the luxuries afforded to him as the only child of a wealthy senator had left him familiar with pools stocked with large carp that took food right from the hand of anyone who was lucky enough to be allowed into the otherwise parched stillness of the walled topiary gardens lovingly tended by the extended family for generations.\par
\tab Here in the portal hive where Balthazar was preparing for a travel experience restricted to a select few, it struck home that the Artisan likely knew as much about the reality of such a journey as nearly any other uninitiated soul since his profession had near complete access to pretty much anywhere there were the kind of gardens and oases only bestowed upon the wealthiest of a desert world, and hence this man had unusual wisdom though treated as a practitioner of a menial profession. In fact, due to their intimate associations with the trading guild-families who import the majority of Homeworld's water through the portal as bulk transfers worth a lifetime's ration to the lesser priveliged, the Artisans tended to be acutely aware of the politics of the city-states that controled the portals from which the water was sourced. Their deeply logical and measured philosophies, and conveniently well placed eavesdropping opportunities, often left them with an understanding bordering upon prescient when it came to world political affairs.\par
\par
A few hours previously in this special corner of Homeworld, as the sun was rising to shed the first of the day's warmth onto the antechamber-courtyard walls with their woven something-fruit trees climbing the peeling paint trellises, the water tinkling in the raked gravel and bonsai topiary surrounded fountain spluttered to silence. Although strictly manicured, the courtyard was exceptionally peaceful and comforting in its age and warmth - entirely necessary for those preparing to journey through the arcane gateway hidden deep in the hive buildings. Even as silence descended to shroud the courtyard the Artisan was arriving at the vestibule to the portal hive buildings, although he thought he was to oversee the reception of a water shipment, a steadfastly routine task for one of his seniority in the profession.\par
\tab It remains open to conjecture whether it could be pure coincidence that such a knowledgeable individual would just happen to be called into the portal antechamber-courtyard directly as Balthazar was receiving notification of his mission. It was possibly the biggest decision Balthazar had ever had in his relatively dull life. He found himself mulling over a string of factors ranging from the raw fortune of being offered the chance to undergo portal travel to a different world - something even such a well favoured botany student would normally never dream of, through to the temptation to stay safely at home where he could continue to feed the fish and hide inside the books of his sedate little botany studies with no risk to hide nor hair. Even if he did desperately want to see new places and new people, he had a lot to lose, his current life was by no means unpleasant even if somewhat unadventurous.\par
\tab To complicate the decsion further, this wasn't just a decision about security versus opportunity - the Senate was requesting that as a high status individual with a good understanding of botanical and biochemical arts he should travel to BL to investigate possible methods of securing an improved noetic disruptor for portal travel. Currently BL was the sole source of the drug that acted as this disruptor, a necessity for anyone planning to pass through a portal and emerge with an ounce of sanity remaining. This state of affairs not only left BL with a monopoly on portal travel, but was still a very hit and miss process that made diplomacy even harder due to the risks involved in using the drug leaving a dearth of ambassadors willing to undergo the ordeal. Anyone who could procure a more reliable disruptor drug and source of said drug would be set for life upon safely delivering it to the Homeworld Senate.\par
\tab It was precisely as Balthazar was sitting on a bench in the antechamber-courtyard torn between thoughts of retreat into saftety set against ambition and adventure that the Artisan entered having been diverted from his days duties to see to the fountain. Having ignored the Artisan the whole time he was mulling over the decision and then treated the sage advice not to eat with disdain, Balthazar began to reconsider his aloof attitude and deigned to listen to the old man's words. Although he couldn't know the nature of the mission the Senate entrusted him with, the Artisan had quoted an age-old section of text about travel across the empty deserts separating the Homeworld oases, \par
\tab "A traveller who fights the fall\cf1 -\cf0 fear of nervous excitement will all the more lose anticipation of new opportunities and promise of good things to come to the intensely blinding nerves that cripple even the simplest journey and make adjustment to the destination that much harder." \par
\tab Nodding slowly he looked Balthazar in the eye. "Follow that advice when undergoing portal travel and your life will follow a course much easier, not just as concerns the nearsighted but also those with the wherewithall to conquer worlds". He then spoiled the gravitas of his words with a loud clunk delivered by a metal tool to the fountain base. the sprinkling started up again and light danced round the walls of the coutyard as the water was covered in ripples again.\par
\tab "What's that s'posed to mean?" asked Balthazar, but the voice that responded was behind him. spinning round he saw a familiar face - not one he could place where he he recognised it from, but familiar nonetheless. \par
\par
\pard\qc ***\par
\pard\tab\par
"Those old Artisan guys know what they're on about. If he says don't fight your nerves then listen to him i reckon" My voice must have pushed some recognition into place - i had sat the journeyman exams in the same hall as him, but, being from an unpriveleged family Balthazar had never bothered to give the time of day before. \par
"But he said... Oh... Forget it..." Balthazar had decided to keep his question to himself. He must have been aware that i knew he had thrown-up even though he made no reference to it, instead he beckoned me into the courtyard. I should have been somewhat affronted since he was technically of no higher rank than me - both of us were journeymen, the lowest order granted the honour of travel via portal, but in the real world both of us knew his family were deeply rooted in the Senate and hence he would always hold unspoken sway over me.\par
\tab "You can't seriously be telling me that you have connections enough to be sent through the portal with me?" His eyebrows betrayed hi attempts at nonchalant enquiry - clearly he felt affronted that the exceptional nature of his mission was diminished by sharing it with me. \par
\tab "I'm to be your cultural advisor" i responded, holding back from adding "which means your chaperone, to stop you from making a fool of yourself and the Senate." He knew i meant exactly that without me saying it.\par
\tab "What qualifies \i you\i0  to advise \i me\i0 ?" he sneered, "what do you know of BL?"\par
\tab "I was born there, and, as you should be able to infer, have travelled through the portal before." i was relishing the realisation chasing incredulity across his face, "So although my official title is that of bodyguard, i actually hold rank over you whilst on BL". I let the reality sink in before continuing, "There are some details about the mission that couldn't be disclosed until you had accepted. I've been tasked to fill you in on the details - namely, as you're now aware, the journeyman exams you sat were more than just schooling - they were a basic aptitude test for Senate diplomacy mission work. Your education in biochemical arts and field studies of off world botanicals combined with a Senate approved lineage leaves you perfectly placed to undertake work with the disruptor drug." He was, at least, not so arrogant as to pay no heed to information that could actually affect the mission. Now came the clincher, \par
\tab "BL's history and hence politics etc. are somewhat inconvenient as far as Senate desires are concerned. The relatively recent reopening of the portal in the C-S/T/M on BL has created a massive imbalance in the already delicate politics of BL, and now that C-S/T/M is effectively independent of the other C-S/TM's as long as it has drug-resin to trade, the Nomad drug-caravans that travel from the Cloud-Forest Alchemists are a particular weakpoint in the trade chain that keeps the portal system operational. As a result of this power imbalance, the other C-S/T/Ms are preparing to besiege C-S/T/M  - effectively initiating all out war. lthough it is unrealistic to expect you to thwart war plans of entire C-S/T/M's, it is distinctly possible that we could find a means of producing a synthetic or improved disruptor-drug not reliant upon the drug-resin form the alchemists if only you could learn the true process of drug-resin production that the Cloud-Forest Alchemists keep secret."\par
\par
\pard\qc ***\par
\pard\par
Although i had managed to give a brief outline of the BL world political situation, i didnt get the chance to embue Balthazar with the majority of the info he would need to have half a chance of achieving his mission in BL - time was running short and we were called to meet with the [Hive-Monks]? for instruction on portal travel. Although i had travelled once before as a child, it was long enough ago that i needed to be refreshed on the details of the ceremony. The hive-monk assigned to talk us through the intricacies of the journey and the necessary preparation was, like all the other hive-monks, bald and ancient. so ancient he looked liek he had been sundried on a rooftop for a hundred years then packed away for storage in a tiny tiny space. the only feature on him that wasn't ochre coloured and wizened was his knee-length white moustache.\par
\tab The monk spoke for a few hours about the rituals and meditations that must be followed to prepare the intellect and soul for the pitfalls of portal travel - what it all boiled down to as far as i had ascertained over the years was that technically, all a traveller needed to do was get enough of the disruptor-drug into his system to ensure they weren't still intellectually and spiritually attached to this reality when passing through the portal itself. the details of the necessary preparations needed to achieve this were somewhat more complex. Not only was there a risk of either failing to travel or even worse, end up 'elsewhere' due to not reaching the appropriate intellectual and spiritual detachment, but also the traveller, whilst under the influence of the disruptor-drug, was at great risk of becoming a victim of the Malignancy. Although a risk prevalent at all times when messing with the disruptor-drug, and those especially vulnerable such as [?twins? pregnant?], being [\cf1 turned?\cf0 ] were always at risk when using portals, contrary to popular belief, users/abusers of the the unrefined drug-resin were not in any significant danger.\par
\tab When the monk left us to begin our meditiations in the antechamber Balthazar suddenly overcame his reticence to treat me like a equal being [or was in such great need of a freindly ear to talk out his fears] and began to demonstrate some of the reason why he had been selected for this mission - he very clearly knew a great deal about the actual drug and the theory behind it's use. We were supposed to be sitting in silence and using breathing techniques to clear all clouding thoughts from our conciousness so as to allow the purifying incense smoke to cleanse our souls. It was in fact far more comforting and useful to listen to Balthazar explain about the disruptor-drug.\par
"disruptor-drug is a noetic disruptor..."\par
"know-what?"\par
"'noetic' - pertaining to the mind, especially to its rational and intellectual faculties", he flailed around trying to regain his mental thread "to pass through safely the user must insufflate or inject a dose..." \par
"insufflate?"\par
"the practice of inhaling substances into a body orifice" he looked distinctly more annoyed, I could see he was gonna get really annoyed if i didn't shut up - i decided to let him speak and ask my questions later.\par
"...or inject a dose," he repeated, "whilst in position, else at best just pass through to the other side as if nothing had occured, or even worse, as with some attempts the at improving the drug, pass but end up somewhere with no contiguous conciousness hence no way to return home." \par
He was spewing out the textbooks word for word but i hadn't read all the textbooks had to say and so not only was the human voice comforting in the stillness of he antechamber but also it was helping soothe my anxieties by helping me understand what to expect.\par
"It is worthy of note that when the disruptor-drug is insufflated through the nostrils users report markedly diminished euphoria for increased 'spiritual' qualities of effect, hence it is generally more useful to use the nasal method to administer the traditional disruptor-drug." Continuing, "The the disruptor-drug/portal experience is short, but generally incredibly intense. Onset is incredibly fast, the acceleration like being fired from a bow. It engages and envelopes every sense, but varies greatly from one individual to the next, some people finding the disruptor-drug/travel experiences difficult to integrate and hence experiencing unsettling thoughts and feelings for days after use."\par
Now came some real interesting stuff, since it explained the real reasons behind the monks' weird rituals "the disruptor-drug doesn't work every time. If the traveller fails to achieve the desired affects they have to wait an hour or more for the drug to be metabolised out of their system before they can try again the exact mechanism is not fully understood, although it is suspected there is some variety of tolerance occuring that involves the blood-brain barrier chemistry. Due to these issues, even though the drug is refined and advanced compared to the raw fungus extract enjoyed by the natives, there is great scope for improvment in the..." i never got to hear the end of this sentence or the rest of the intricasies of the disruptor-drug sciences because a great reverberating wall of sound swept through the hive complex - the big iron bell in the portal chamber had been struck, signalling hat the time was ready, the portals would now be in conjuntion and the time for travel was nigh...\par
\par
\par
We stood to be met by a monk who beckoned us to enter the actual portal chamber itself. As the lingering resonance of the great bell faded i noticed the portal chamber was far from quiet - settling down into the cushions inside the intricately wrought transport ring that was itself only the actual focus point of the smaller person portal, i realised that although there were large censers of coloured smoking perfumed herbs burning supposedly to protect the cargo transits from the malevolence, there was a hum of extractor fans to ventilate enough of the smoke for the room to be breatheable. these only became audible when the monks damped the bell and ceased pottering about tending to the portal workings. Already sat in the ring was a grossly overweight merchant dressed in rich silks and filigreed with jewellery.  we were to watched him consume the disruptor-drug. much like a Homeworld tea ceremony, the drug and associated accoutrements were carried in on a beautifully embroidered cloth covered tray. At this point the ceremony diverged from both my previous experience and Balthazar's textbook recital, as the refined disruptor-drug came in the form of a single light blue crystal which was loaded onto a gauze and slipped into a small, s-shaped glass pipe with a sort of bubble a one end. The monk then held this bubble part with the gauze and crystal in it over a strangely carved candle and it immediately began to give off thick creamy smoke which filled the bubble. he passed the pipe to the merchant and who inhaled deeply, taking in all the fumes, whilst the monk readied a cushion placing it to catch the pipe. For a second nothing happened then a serene smile spread across his face. There was what can only be described as a deafening silence - not just quiet but a lack of noise so intense it was as if something unheard was drowning out everything else, and this coincided with a dimmin of the lights. as the light and sound returned to the chamber only one thing seemed to have changed; the pipe fell, deftly caught on the cushion held by the waiting monk, because the merchant was gone. \par
\tab Immediately as the room returned to normal (yes, i'm aware that such a room can never reasonably be described as normal) the monks started bustling about getting it ready for the next traveller. The next traveller was to be me. I took my place in the ring, sining deep into the cushions. The monk prepared the pipe and crystal as before, when the bubble was filled with smoke i took the proffered pipe and sucked in the smoke. It had a sweet and cloying taste which caused me to cough despite my attempts not to waste the lungful. I'm afraid my words will never do justice when descibing what happened next. As i inhaled the smoke i noticed the pattern of the thrumming fans as they went in and out of phase - this became more rapid, loud and metallic until it was nearly unbearable, yet neither Balthazar or the monks appeared to notice. The universe was being torn asunder but i was alone - as the final effects of the drug kicked in i felt the urge to sneeze combined with an intense ear pop, then everything seemed to turn black\cf1 .\cf0  i stared at the blackness waiting for the lights to come back on - suddenly i realised they were on. except it wasn't artificial light from the ring - this was beautiful soft pink light coming through a window, from a sun close to the horizon. i was in a completely different place. I was home.\par
\cf1\par
*The Balthazar needs a deeper motive to his actions - why does he care so much? for the story's sake once he gets there he wants to be able to go home, he wants to stay alive, he wants to find out the answers to the mystery - but why? cos he actually does belong to a trader guild-family, and wants to take the most powerful position through improving the drug. His first taste of power comes through blackmailing the alchemists that he already has developed the new drug and simply needs to get back to his trader guild-family/culture people to stop them releasing it before the rains are over which they will do if he doesnt reappear. the girl knos he has the secret in his head and myust get it out but not that it exists nowhere else - she is using him to try and get the secrets for her clan hence giving them the power over all others. this is why the girls helps him even though it's not to the advantage of all the different clans and so is devisive, and helps the Balthazar become ambitious...\par
\tab tbut, the end does introduce us to the concept that although the Balthazar starts off snobbish and superior, ad ends powerful and more ambitious, he does pick up some humility andrespect for the B-L world.\par
