I wasn't left with very long to aclimatise to the change in surroundings since i was stirred from my reverie by the portly merchant who had travelled before me embroiled in a heated discussion with one of the tech-priests operating the portal only to storm out of the room still cursing. Whatever was going on i didn't get to discover because there was a loud splash and a yell which was cut off in a sudden gurgle. Balthazar had arrived through the cargo portal which was located over a large stone cistern full of water ready to discharge to Homeworld. Diving in to the surprisingly warm water i swam to the bottom, which was only a matter of six feet below and dragged Balthazar to the surface. though taller than me he was somewhat lighter famed and so getting him to a position where he could draw breath wasnot too arduous. Naturally i was distracted by the initial shock of the whole situation and was driven only by thoughts of how fortunate he was that i had been there, able to swim and hence rescue him, for no-one from Homeworld would ever have experienced enough water in one place to have been able to learn to swim. then it started to dawn on me as we climbed over the edge of the cistern, this was clearly no accident. someone had to have inntentionally rigged the personal transit portal to exit into the cargo portal. Since it was highly unlikely for the Homeworld monks or any others native to Homeworld to have sabotaged things at the outbound end of the journey, it surely had to be someone from BL. \par
\par
As the portal tech-priests ran over to check both us and the rings to rectify the dangerous transporter set-up, Balthazar seemingly unphased by his ordeal, lost the strange expression on his face when he caught the suns' rays scraping under the cloud layer to set him sneezing. after a bout of five or six sneezes in quick succession he muttered "damned stuff making me sneeze. at least it wasn't that old stuff that had to be insufflated, our technology is obviously improving every day which is a far cry from the situation round here..." then he started to laugh. confused i looked askance at him, "i'm soaked! back home i would be woth my own weight in anything you could offer me except maybe disruptor-drug!"\par
As it dawned on me how long i had been since i was properly drenched i too began to laugh, "you're gonna have to get used to soakings round here, it rains sixteen days out of every twenty four, in a pattern that is so regular it runs like clockwork, and has done for millenia" \par
\par
After convincing the tech-priests that we were fine and merely wet through we were led through to an adjoining room with an amazing vista out of a panaoramic window which revealed that all though we were deep below a fortified city carved into a rock outcrop, we were on a projection of stone that jutte out from a cliff over the cloud forest giving an unparalled view horizontally across the upper forest canopy with nearly one hundred and eighty degres of vision to allow an outstanding sunset made more special than could be achieved on nearly any other known world due to the unusual colouration of the light given of by the Beta-Lyrae binary star pair. Although shining through some cloud and haze, and the atmospheric conditions diffusing the light such that the exact nature of the twin suns' mutually destructive dance induced sculpture couldn't be seen from BL's surface, the quality of the light reaching the surface when shining under the cloud layer building over the forest was simply beautiful. we were both silenced, dumbstruck by the sheer awsome beauty of the sight. compared to the baking yellow ball that cooked Homeworld day in, day out, all year round, this place certainly felt special, and even though the humidity was, in comparison, so oppressive it felt distinctly harder to breathe, nevertheless the appeal of this tepui/mesa as a living space was quite apparent. Eager to get out of the humidty of the lower levels of the city and see more of the upper levels, we both hurriedly changed to clothing provioded by the city-state.fresh   \par
As we finished dressing there was a conveniently timed knock at the door and upon a response from Balthazar the tech-priest who i had witnessed arguing with the fat merchant entred and handed a message-tablet to Balthazar. To my astonishment the tablet was noticeably covered in a very specific script - surprising because it was the special coded language used by the trading guild-families primarily to send secure messages back and forth between the different portal enabled worlds. that Balthazar could read and understand this coded script raised questions i really didn't want to dwell on right now, but definitely was going to be food for thought later on. Balthazar walked to the door, opened it, and peered around - apparently satisfied no-one was eavesdropping he walked over to me and began to read from the tablet in a hushed tone,\par
"the 'improved' disruptor-drug that the senate sent you through the portal with degrades incredibly fast and hence you cannot use the doses you were given as a means of return. since threats of impending war, nomadic -tribe attacks and sabotage has stalled supplies from the cloud-forest alchemists and the city-state stockpiles have run out, your mission's success will be your only realistic opportunity of getting home. the senate didn't plan of informing you of this \cf1 fait accomplis\cf0  until much later in your dealings with the city-state. hopefully this information will allow you to make some more informed decisions and leave you in a better negotiating position. XX\cf1 "\cf0  he looked toward me, stonyfaced.\cf0\par
"You understand what this means?" Balthazar looked concerned.\par
"We can't go back through the portal without visiting the cloud-forest alchemists?" i paused to think for a second "which means we have to do some very cunning diplomacy to calm the troubles brewing between the city-states?"\par
"Worse..." intoned Balthazar still appearing expressionless except for his brow which was starting to furrow, "we cant rely on help from the Homeworld senate or the City-State unless we can make our interests their interests."\par
Another knock at the door caused both Balthazar and i to leap like startled lizards, and after stowing the tablet in his robes Balthazar went to the door to receive a summons from the city-Sytate council of elders.\par
\par
As befitting diplomats from a portal-network world, the council were to recieve us in the grand hall high up in the City-State castle-complex, so we got a grand tour of the buildings as we followed the courtier guiding us through the maze of stairs, corridoors, ladders and galleries. \cf0 The castle-complex itself was basically a very heavily fortified large castle built on such a steep outcrop of rock that it looked more a vertical military installation than a city, most rooves were effectively floors as well, it was a city of endless stairs and ladders. although populous and busy, and the hub of worldwide trade and the very economy of BL, it was nevertheless very ancient, and although it was far above the treetops of the cloud-forest avoiding the clogging leaves and detritus, jungle creepers and the more tenacious climbing plants had a hold and were starting to evolve enough to take over parts of the fabric of the building, though the regular rains easily washed the majority of any foreign matter away. In fact, as we walked i couldn't help but notice that every corridor and gallery had a drainage channel or a gutter, shutters and overhanging eaves, every stairway was angled inwards and every flight of stairs striated with carved grips. the rooves that wern't floors were incredibly steep, ringed with guttering and tiled for major waterproofing. There was immense \cf0 capacity for drainage, guttering, spouts, gargoyles, channels, culverts, and more. these thoughts were soon cleared from my head as we entered the great hall, with it's immense high ceiling, beautiful intricate tiled wood floor and, sat along a table on a raised dais at one end, a row of incredibly ancient looking heavily bearded, robed men.\par
